title: For Sale:  Astra 600/43 WW II 9 MM - $475
postcontent:
WW II Astra 600/43 - 9 mm Lugar (9 x 19), 7 + 1 - Mfg in Spain in 1945 - 95% + blue finish, orig checkered walnut grips in excellent condition. Has lanyard ring on butt stock. No import marks, only Spanish proof marks. Serial # 277XX
All matching numbers on frame, slide, barrel, barrel cap and on one of the 2 magazines.
Matching numbered magazine also has a 1 stamped on it, the other magazine is not matching numbered but stamped with number 2, so it probably has always been with the pistol. Has original black leather flap holster with extra magazine pocket and it also appears to have always been with this pistol. 
Serial number is correct to be part of the 2nd contract pistol shipment sold to Nazi Germany by Spain but never shipped because of the allied invasion of France. 
After WW II Spain sold this gun with many others for a second time to Germany. 
This time to the West German police force and it is appropriately marked LBPN which indicates Lower Saxony Barracks Police ended up with it in their arsenal. 
This is an excellent pistol with a lot of history, I can only guess how it made it to the US after WW II. 
It will make a great addition to any collection.
Pistol cycles perfectly with both magazines and is accurate.
I have 11 pictures other than the 3 posted here I can email if interested.
Wayne

The M24 series is a line of Mauser pattern bolt-action battle rifles produced for use by the Yugoslavian military. They are similar to the Czech vz. 24 rifle, featuring open sights, 8x57mm IS chambering, carbine-length barrels, hardwood stocks, and straight bolt handles. All M24 series weapons are designed to accept the M-24/48 pattern bayonet.[1]



THe first Mauser-pattern rifle produced in Yugoslavia was the M24. Its predecessor, the FN Model 1924 had been produced for the Yugoslav army by FN Herstal until the Ministry and FN signed a contract on the purchase of the licence for production of rifles 7.9 mm M 24. Nearly all M24's were produced either before or during World War II, at the Kragujevac Arsenal plant. The M24 and Model 1924 are nearly identical.[2]

The final additions to the M24 family were the M24/47 and M24/52 rifles. Both were produced by reworking existing prewar Model 1924 rifles after World War II at the Zastava Arms (formally Kragujevac Arsenal) plant, which was at that time under the control of the postwar communist government. "47" and "52" indicate the beginning of the rebuild program for each respective model: 1947 for the M24/47 and 1952 for the M24/52. One common misconception is that the M24/47 rifles were produced only in 1947; actually, the rebuild program lasted into the early 1950s alongside new production of M48 rifles. Minor cosmetic differences exist between the M24/47 and M24/52, but the rifles are nearly identical to one another and to their predecessors, the Model 1924 and M24.[3]

M24 series rifles were used by the Royal Yugoslav Army and the Yugoslav Partisans during World War II.

Mechanics: The action functions perfectly. This is a 9+1 single stack with a magazine safety disconnect, safety/de-cocker and bobbed hammer.  The original magazine is  provided. The magazine has both sides marked with 2 through 9 witness holes, “10 MM” and an S&W logo.

Assessment: The S&W 1066 is the carry version of their single stack 10MM, with low mount Novak’s sights and a bobbed hammer. The 10MM was designed by Col. Jeff Cooper to be more powerful and flatter shooting than the .45 ACP. It is primarily used for rural law enforcement, personal defense and hunting. Paraphrased from Wikipedia “The government of Denmark has issued the 10MM to members of the Sirius Sledge Patrol in Greenland as a defense against polar bears which the unit might encounter"

This all steel pistol with it's fully supported barrel can handle ALL 10 mm loads, buffalo bore, full house, critical defense, etc.  Muzzle velocity's are achievable in excess of 1500 FPS.  This is one of 5,067 made ever!

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1906 Excellent Condition
postcontent: Model 1906 winchester out of a private collection, Extremely RARE. Has been in this collection since the early 60's. I am rating this rifle at 95%, but you look at the pictures and be your own judge. The 06's where MFG. from 1906 to 1932, with about 848,000 produced. But post WWII Winchester is supposed to have taken the remaining parts produced some more 06's. The serial on this one is 853810. Using the book ( Winchester Slide-Action on 1890's & 1906's by Ned Schwing ) for information. The wood is from a very early 1906. The barrel marking is the 6th and a series of 7 markings. The barrel has the proof marking to show it has been rebarreled at the factory and has the crowned barrel done post WWII 06's. Has the 62 receiver that the very last 06's had with no Winchester marking on the tang. So if you want a RARE 06 here it is, MFG post WWII. 14 years after product ceased, and here we are 68 years later with the gun still in excellect conditio

title: For Sale:  S&W 38/44 Transitional postwar Heavy Duty
postcontent:
1946 manufacture date SN S65533

Gun is in excellent condition considering the age. All serial numbers on the gun match; the barrel, frame, cylinder and ejector star. The grips are SN 73517 so just a few years off, but period correct. These grips are $200+ alone Transitional features: Old style hammer, satin blue, 'Made In USA' one-liner, large S&W logo on right side, five screw frame, larger ejector rod tip with appropriate cutout. 
Lockup and timing are solid, as they should be. Grips are in very good condition, with no major chips. There is a slight amount of holster wear as can be seen, but there are little signs of firing. No torch cutting or other signs of damage near the cone area. Backstrap has some light wear. Handling marks are present in a few places, mainly on the high edges. Still a very nice, fully functioning example of a scarce model with a rich history made just after WWII. No factory work dates, and no evidence the pistol has been altered in any way. The finish is original.

title: For Sale:  Hi-point Front Pocket Concealment Holster for Ruger LC9
postcontent:
Hi-point Front Pocket Concealment Holster for Ruger LC9, While limiting the carrier to a relatively small handgun, pocket carry offers some unique advantages. Not only is the handgun completely covered and concealed, but the gun carrier can casually place a hand on the holstered/pocketed pistol if a nonspecific threat materializes and the fastest draw is to have the gun already in hand.

The Reloading Zone
11407 W. I-70 Frontage Rd N.
Wheat Ridge, Colorado  80033
303-431-GUNS

Next Class Saturday September 13th from 8 to 4

The NRA Basic Metallic Cartridge Reloading course exposes students to the basics of reloading centerfire metallic cartridges with little or no prior experience in reloading.
Although the course can be completed as quickly as eight hours, the amount of information presented, and the probability of intensive question and answer sessions on the included topics, makes it likely that the course will take longer.
Students will receive the NRA Guide to Reloading handbook and intensive lessons on the basics of reloading.
Course Goal
“To provide beginning reloaders with the basic knowledge, skills, and attitude necessary to safety reload metallic cartridges.”
—NRA Basic Metallic Cartridge Reloading Course Lesson Plans
Lessons
1.Introduction to Reloading and Reloading Safety
2.Centerfire Cartridge Components
3.Using the Reloading Manual and Reloading Data
4.Metallic Cartridge Reloading Equipment
5.The Metallic Cartridge Reloading Process
6.Basic Metallic Cartridge Reloading Practical Exercise
7.Course Review and Examination
Prerequisites
The are no prerequisites for taking this course, and the material is accessible to organized and conscientious people. Be aware that attention to detail is a vital skill in safe reloading.
Course Completion
Students will receive feedback on the practical exercises conducted during the course. There is a short written test on the lesson material at the end of the course.

postcontent:
The Reloading Zone
11407 W. I-70 Frontage Rd N.
Wheat Ridge, Colorado  80033
303-431-GUNS

The NRA Basic Metallic Cartridge Reloading course exposes students to the basics of reloading centerfire metallic cartridges with little or no prior experience in reloading.
Although the course can be completed as quickly as eight hours, the amount of information presented, and the probability of intensive question and answer sessions on the included topics, makes it likely that the course will take longer.
Students will receive the NRA Guide to Reloading handbook and intensive lessons on the basics of reloading.
Course Goal
“To provide beginning reloaders with the basic knowledge, skills, and attitude necessary to safety reload metallic cartridges.”
—NRA Basic Metallic Cartridge Reloading Course Lesson Plans
Lessons
1.Introduction to Reloading and Reloading Safety
2.Centerfire Cartridge Components
3.Using the Reloading Manual and Reloading Data
4.Metallic Cartridge Reloading Equipment
5.The Metallic Cartridge Reloading Process
6.Basic Metallic Cartridge Reloading Practical Exercise
7.Course Review and Examination
Prerequisites
The are no prerequisites for taking this course, and the material is accessible to organized and conscientious people. Be aware that attention to detail is a vital skill in safe reloading.
Course Completion
Students will receive feedback on the practical exercises conducted during the course. There is a short written test on the lesson material at the end of the course.

Sighting-in made simple. 1) Aim at a fixed point (target or bull's eye) and fire a 3-5 shot group to establish your point of aim. 2) Clamp the gun in the vise and use the adjustments to center the reticle on the point of aim (target). 3) Without moving the gun or the vise, use the adjustments on the sight to move the reticle to the center of the group. I am offering Minnesota, Florida & WI (Wisconsin residents get their Wisconsin permit on the MN course) Concealed Carry Classes at the rate of $70, With groups of 5+ the group organizer  will get a discounted rate of $40 
(Gives you MN+FL certificates - WISC Recognizes MN Cert) 
* RENTAL of a Ruger MKI (.22LR) Firearm for class room portion is Provided FREE but with limited availability* You should bring (1) 50 round box of ammo for the class. If you cannot, maybe I can help.

This is a Completely Legal classes for which you can submit your paperwork to the appropriate State authorities and obtain your carry permits with my training... 

I have been doing this for a long time: (over 1,000 students trained between our instructors) I have heard the horror stories from other clients.. There are instructors giving Cut-Rate and Questionable classes. Some of my Competitors give you Lunch or other gimmicks and charge $100.. Or say they charge less, until you have to pay a Range Fee. Or have to buy their ammunition.. etc..
* My philosophy is to not price gouge you out of your permit to carry. Providing you a low cost (not cut rate) class, and not charge you every time you turn around. Semi-Automatic, Preferably a Double stack 10 round magazine (NO REVOLVERS) We're just putting holes in paper 
Classes are held up-to-DAILY, (Generally on Saturdays & Sundays noon and Week days 8 or 9 am and again at 5pm) but I will do a class on other days/Times. I Also do individual classes but prefer that you bring a few others with you to make it more worthwhile for me... (I thank you in advance)

Check out my website for additional information;
www.bahrindustries.com/carry.html
If You want me to Leave the Pine City Area to do a class, I can certainly do that, but I may charge up to $100 depending on number of occupants attending the class.. 
(the reason is I have to rent a building to hold the class, and also rent a range, it's certainly not worthwhile for me to leave my scheduled area to do a class. Typically the student is saving upwards of $50 by going to my classes, most all instructors charge $120 and up, I've seen $200) 

It is really easiest to contact me directly, and we can discuss this.
